rey, England","Kingston upon Thames, Surrey, England":"Kingston upon Thames, Surrey, England","Harrow on the Hill, Middlesex, England":"Harrow on the Hill, Middlesex, England","Stanmore, Middlesex, England":"Stanmore, Middlesex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Aylward","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from a Middle English personal name, <i>Ailward</i>, Old English <i>Æthelweard</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘noble’ + ‘guardian’. This English name has been established in Ireland since at least the 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Alward","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Alward</i>, <i>Elward</i>, a shortened form of several Old English names, such as <i>Ælfweard</i> (Middle English <i>Alfward</i>), <i>Ealdweard</i>, and (especially in Devon) <i>Æthelweard</i>, which survives as Middle English   Aylward  , <i>Alward</i>, and probably <i>Elward</i>.","North German: variant of   Alwardt   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Elward","meanings":["English (Glamorgan): variant of   Aylward   or   Alward  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalen